<p></p>.<p><a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/chronic_cough/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Cough</a> is a rapid expulsion of air from the <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/image-collection/lungs_picture/picture.htm" rel="img" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">lungs</a> 
typically in order to
clear the lung airways of fluids, mucus, or material. <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/cold_flu_cough_relief_pictures_slideshow/article.htm" rel="slide" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">Cough</a> is also called tussis. Cough can be categorized as acute (less than 
three weeks) or chronic (greater than three weeks).</p>.<p>Chronic cough has many possible causes, including infectious and noninfectious conditions and diseases.
</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>Kasper, D.L., et al., eds. <i>Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 19th Ed</i>. United States: McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.</p>